name: Document
comment:
The base class for all documents.

Each web page loaded in the browser has its own angular-mock.Document object, which is typically an angular-mock.HtmlDocument.

If you aren't comfortable with DOM concepts, see the Dart tutorial Target 2: Connect Dart & HTML.

nodeType.name: nodeType
nodeType.comment:
The type of node.

This value is one of:

  • angular-mock.Node.ATTRIBUTE_NODE if this node is an attribute.
  • [CDATA_SECTION_NODE] if this node is a dart-dom-html.CDataSection.
  • angular-mock.Node.COMMENT_NODE if this node is a dart-dom-html.Comment.
  • [DOCUMENT_FRAGMENT_NODE] if this node is a dart-dom-html.DocumentFragment.
  • angular-mock.Node.DOCUMENT_NODE if this node is a angular-mock.Document.
  • [DOCUMENT_TYPE_NODE] if this node is a DocumentType node.
  • angular-mock.Node.ELEMENT_NODE if this node is an dart-dom-html.Element.
  • angular-mock.Node.ENTITY_NODE if this node is an entity.
  • [ENTITY_REFERENCE_NODE] if this node is an entity reference.
  • angular-mock.Node.NOTATION_NODE if this node is a notation.
  • [PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION_NODE] if this node is a dart-dom-html.ProcessingInstruction.
  • angular-mock.Node.TEXT_NODE if this node is a dart-dom-html.Text node.

Other resources

  • Node.nodeType from MDN.

querySelector.name: querySelector
querySelector.comment:
Finds the first descendant element of this document that matches the specified group of selectors.

Unless your webpage contains multiple documents, the top-level angular-mock.Document.querySelector method behaves the same as this method, so you should use it instead to save typing a few characters.

angular-mock.Document.querySelector.selectors should be a string using CSS selector syntax.

var element1 = document.querySelector('.className');
var element2 = document.querySelector('#id');

For details about CSS selector syntax, see the CSS selector specification.

querySelectorAll.name: querySelectorAll
querySelectorAll.comment:
Finds all descendant elements of this document that match the specified group of selectors.

Unless your webpage contains multiple documents, the top-level angular-mock.Document.querySelectorAll method behaves the same as this method, so you should use it instead to save typing a few characters.

angular-mock.Document.querySelectorAll.selectors should be a string using CSS selector syntax.

var items = document.querySelectorAll('.itemClassName');

For details about CSS selector syntax, see the CSS selector specification.

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides angular-mock.Document.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

runtimeType.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and angular-mock.Document.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the angular-mock.Document.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

append.name: append
append.comment:
Adds a node to the end of the child angular-mock.Document.nodes list of this node.

If the node already exists in this document, it will be removed from its current parent node, then added to this node.

This method is more efficient than nodes.add, and is the preferred way of appending a child node.

clone.name: clone
clone.comment:
Returns a copy of this node.

If angular-mock.Document.clone.deep is true, then all of this node's children and decendents are copied as well. If angular-mock.Document.clone.deep is false, then only this node is copied.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
angular-mock.Document.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to angular-mock.Document.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If angular-mock.Document.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of angular-mock.Document.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.
